---
/**
 * Hub: capital gains. The shared investment engine's home page. Worked example
 * computed by investmentTax(), the same function the island uses.
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import CapitalGainsCalculator from '../../components/calculators/CapitalGainsCalculator.tsx';
import { investmentTax, stateGainsTax } from '../../lib/capital-gains';
import { formatMoney, formatPct } from '../../lib/tax-engine';
import { states } from '../../data/states';

const ex = investmentTax({
  status: 'single', otherOrdinaryIncome: 80000,
  shortTermGains: 5000, longTermGains: 20000, applyStandardDeduction: true,
});
// The same long-term gain taxed as short-term, to show the holding-period gap.
const asShort = investmentTax({
  status: 'single', otherOrdinaryIncome: 80000, shortTermGains: 25000, applyStandardDeduction: true,
});
// The same $5k short-term / $20k long-term gains across four state treatments.
const stateEx = ['CA', 'SC', 'MO', 'WA'].map((c) => ({ name: states[c].name, ...stateGainsTax(c, 80000, 5000, 20000, 'single') }));
---

<Base
  title="Capital gains tax calculator 2026 — short vs long-term"
  description="Calculate 2026 federal capital gains tax: short-term at ordinary rates, long-term at 0/15/20%, loss netting and carryover, plus the 3.8% NIIT surtax."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Capital gains tax calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">One day past a year changes the rate. This shows by how much.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Sell an asset for more than you paid and the profit is a capital gain. Held a
    year or less, it is short-term and taxed like wages. Held more than a year, it
    is long-term and taxed at 0%, 15% or 20% depending on your income. This nets
    your gains and losses, applies the right rate to each, adds the 3.8% net
    investment income tax where it bites, and carries any excess loss forward.
  </p>

  <CapitalGainsCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example — {formatMoney(5000)} short-term and {formatMoney(20000)} long-term gains</h2>
  <p>
    A single filer with {formatMoney(80000)} of other income realizes {formatMoney(5000)}
    of short-term and {formatMoney(20000)} of long-term gains:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>Tax</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Short-term gain ({formatMoney(ex.netShortTerm)}) at ordinary rates</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.ordinaryTax)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Long-term gain ({formatMoney(ex.netLongTerm)}) at 0/15/20%</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.preferentialTax)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Total federal tax on the gains</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.totalInvestmentTax)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Effective rate on the gains</td><td>{formatPct(ex.effectiveRateOnInvestment)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The long-term rate does the work: {formatMoney(ex.netLongTerm)} of long-term gain
    costs {formatMoney(ex.preferentialTax)} at 15%. Had that same {formatMoney(20000)}
    been short-term — sold before the one-year mark — the whole {formatMoney(25000)}
    would be ordinary income and the tax on it would be {formatMoney(asShort.ordinaryTax)},
    roughly {formatMoney(asShort.ordinaryTax - ex.totalInvestmentTax)} more. That gap is
    the reward for holding past a year.
  </p>

  <h2>How your state changes it</h2>
  <p>
    Federal is only half the story. On the same {formatMoney(5000)} short-term and
    {formatMoney(20000)} long-term gains, four states show the whole range of how
    states treat gains:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>State</th><th>Treatment</th><th>State tax on the gains</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      {stateEx.map((s) => (
        <tr>
          <td>{s.name}</td>
          <td>{s.treatment === 'none' ? 'No tax on gains' : s.treatment === 'excluded' ? 'Excludes part of long-term gains' : s.treatment === 'special' ? 'Standalone excise' : 'Taxed as ordinary income'}</td>
          <td>{formatMoney(s.stateTax)}</td>
        </tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    California taxes the gains at its full ordinary rate. South Carolina excludes
    44% of the long-term gain first. Missouri, which exempted capital gains in 2025,
    charges nothing. Washington's {formatMoney(0)} here is not a mistake — its 7%
    excise only bites on long-term gains above a large annual exemption
    (about {formatMoney(278000)}), so a {formatMoney(20000)} gain is under it. Pick
    your state in the calculator to see your own figure.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What is the difference between short and long-term gains?</h3>
    <p>
      The holding period. One year or less is short-term, taxed at your ordinary
      income rate (up to 37%). More than one year is long-term, taxed at 0%, 15%
      or 20%. The clock runs from the day after you bought to the day you sold.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Who pays 0% on long-term gains?</h3>
    <p>
      Filers whose taxable income (including the gain) stays under the 0% ceiling —
      {formatMoney(49450)} for a single filer in 2026, {formatMoney(98900)} for a
      couple. The gain stacks on top of your other income, so a large gain can
      fill the 0% band and spill into 15%. The calculator handles the stacking.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Can I deduct capital losses?</h3>
    <p>
      Yes. Losses first offset gains of the same type, then the other type. A net
      loss beyond that deducts up to {formatMoney(3000)} against ordinary income
      per year ({formatMoney(1500)} if married filing separately), and anything
      left carries forward to future years indefinitely.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What is the 3.8% net investment income tax?</h3>
    <p>
      An extra 3.8% on investment income once your modified AGI passes
      {formatMoney(200000)} (single) or {formatMoney(250000)} (joint). It applies
      to the smaller of your net investment income and the amount over the
      threshold, so it phases in rather than hitting all at once. The calculator
      adds it automatically.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Does my state tax capital gains too?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      Usually yes — pick your state above and the calculator adds it. Most states
      tax gains as ordinary income with no preferential rate. A handful differ:
      Washington levies a standalone 7% excise on large long-term gains, several
      states (South Carolina, Wisconsin, North Dakota and others) exclude part of
      long-term gains, Hawaii and Montana apply a reduced rate, and nine states —
      including Missouri, which exempted capital gains in 2025 — do not tax them.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/cost-basis-calculator/">Cost basis calculator</a> — FIFO, LIFO and specific-lot basis</li>
    <li><a href="/dividend-tax-calculator/">Dividend tax calculator</a> — qualified vs ordinary</li>
    <li><a href="/crypto-tax-calculator/">Crypto tax calculator</a> — coins, staking and NFTs</li>
    <li><a href="/rsu-tax-calculator/">Equity compensation</a> — RSUs, ISOs, NSOs, ESPP, QSBS</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Estimate for the 2026 tax year using the standard deduction. Federal by default;
    pick a state to add its treatment of gains. Not tax advice.
  </p>
</Base>
